{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>The general (type II) secretion pathway (GSP) within Gram-negative bacteria is a signal sequence-dependent process responsible for protein export [[cite:PUB00005409], [cite:PUB00005523], [cite:PUB00002179]], including virulence factors. The process has two stages, exoproteins are first translocated across the inner membrane by the general signal-dependent export pathway (GEP), and then across the outer membrane by a species-specific accessory mechanism. One of the proteins involved in the GSP is termed general secretion pathway protein G (GSPG). This protein shares several sequence similarities with bacterial fimbrial protein, or pilin, the major structural protein of pili [[cite:PUB00002231], [cite:PUB00002265]]. Pili are polar flexible filamentous adhesions ~2500 nm in length, and diameter ~5.4 nm. Fimbrial and GSPG proteins share the following characteristics; a methylated, hydrophobic N-terminal residue; a hydrophobic leader peptide of 5-10 residues, terminating with glycine; glutamate as the fifth residue of the mature sequence; and a highly hydrophobic N-terminal. This system is homologous to the type IV pilus biogenesis and includes different proteins, termed psudopilins, which are structurally homologous to the type IV pilins [[cite:PUB00094517], [cite:PUB00053545]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR045584", "name" "Pilin-like", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"prints" {"PR00813" "BCTERIALGSPG"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Bacterial general secretion pathway protein G-type pilin", "short" "Bac_GSPG_pilin"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 1, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 3462, "taxa" 17329, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 92062, "sets" 0, "proteins" 46031, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 34710}, "pathways"